Chapter 2: What Records Protect Ownership?
Core Question
What documents keep property from becoming vulnerable?
Understand
Property is protected by memory, but it is also protected by documents.
A family may know a house belongs to them.
But a court, tax office, insurance company, lender, or developer will ask for records.
Property records may include:
Deed
 Title documents
 Mortgage documents
 Tax bills
 Insurance policy
 Will
 Trust documents
 Estate documents
 Death certificates
 Marriage certificates
 Probate documents
 Lease agreements
 Repair receipts
 Utility records
 Survey
 Property tax exemptions
 Business lease
 Church bylaws
 Board minutes
 Articles of incorporation
 Maintenance records
 Permits
 Appraisals
 Loan documents
 Photographs
 Receipts
 Contact list of professionals
Missing documents can create confusion.
Confusion can create loss.
The society should help members understand what documents matter and encourage safe organization.
Do not collect sensitive documents unless the society has strong privacy rules and the member gives consent.
In many cases, the society should provide a checklist and let families keep records privately.
Discuss
What documents do people often lose or misunderstand?
Which documents are needed before crisis?
Who should never see private documents?
What documents can be discussed generally without exposing details?
What professional help may be needed?
