Chapter 4: Who Can Help Without Extracting?
Core Question
Who can provide trustworthy property guidance?
Understand
Property work requires guidance.
But not every professional, investor, developer, lender, or nonprofit is safe.
A society should build a trusted guidance network before crisis.
Possible guidance sources include:
Real estate attorneys
 Estate planning attorneys
 Title professionals
 Housing counselors
 Tax professionals
 Insurance agents
 Home inspectors
 Contractors
 Surveyors
 Appraisers
 Accountants
 Financial counselors
 Tenant organizers
 Community land trust leaders
 Credit unions
 City planning staff
 Code enforcement education contacts
 Heirs property educators
 Church property advisors
 Real estate investors with clear ethics
 Experienced elders
 Property owners who have navigated the process
Trustworthy guidance should be evaluated.
Do they explain clearly?
Do they respect privacy?
Do they pressure people?
Do they disclose fees?
Do they have conflicts of interest?
Do they understand the community?
Do they encourage documentation?
Do they help people keep control?
The society should never send members into property decisions without standards.
Discuss
Who already gives trusted property advice?
Who has harmed people before?
What professions do we need access to?
What standards should guides meet?
How will conflicts of interest be disclosed?
What should be written before referrals are made?
