PART TWO: PROTECT WHAT EXISTS

Chapter 5: Create a Property Records Day
Core Question
Can we help families and members organize documents before crisis?
Understand
A Property Records Day is a simple, powerful first action.
It does not require the society to solve legal problems.
It helps people understand, locate, organize, and protect documents.
A Records Day may include:
Document checklist
 Safe folder setup
 Digital backup guidance
 Property tax calendar
 Insurance review reminder
 Estate planning education
 Heirs property awareness
 Trusted referral list
 Privacy briefing
 Family conversation guide
Do not collect or copy sensitive documents unless there is a clear privacy policy and consent.
The safest version is often:
Teach what documents matter.
Give a checklist.
Help people create their own folder.
Offer referral resources.
Encourage private family follow-up.
Property records are stewardship.
Discuss
Who would benefit from a Records Day?
What documents should people bring or locate?
What should not be collected by the society?
What privacy rules must be stated clearly?
Who can facilitate?
What resource should people leave with?
