Chapter 8: Protect Elders and Family Property
Core Question
How do we honor elders without exposing them?
Understand
Elders often hold memory, property, documents, and community history.
They may also carry vulnerability.
A society must protect elders with dignity.
Elder property stewardship may include:
Helping organize documents
 Encouraging trusted family conversations
 Supporting transportation to appointments
 Creating reminder systems
 Checking on repair needs
 Helping identify predatory offers
 Connecting to estate planning education
 Recording oral history with consent
 Supporting home safety
 Protecting privacy
Do not pressure elders to disclose.
Do not turn elder stories into content without consent.
Do not involve the society in family property conflict without clear boundaries and professional guidance.
Elder stewardship is not control.
It is respectful support.
Discuss
Which elders are holding important property, memory, or documents?
What support would be helpful without being intrusive?
How do we protect elder privacy?
What family conversations may be needed?
What professional guidance may be needed?
What should the society not do?
