Chapter 11: Teach Youth Property Stewardship
Core Question
How do young people learn that land carries responsibility?
Understand
Youth should not only inherit property problems.
They should inherit stewardship knowledge.
Youth can learn:
How deeds work
 Why records matter
 What property taxes are
 What insurance does
 Why maintenance matters
 How neighborhoods change
 What development pressure looks like
 How family property can be lost
 How community spaces are protected
 How to create digital archives
 How to interview elders respectfully
 How to map assets without exposing privacy
Youth property education should be practical.
A young person can help create a family document checklist, map community spaces, record elder property stories with consent, research local history, or assist with a property workshop.
The goal is to train future stewards.
Discuss
What do youth need to know about property?
What property lessons did adults learn too late?
What project could youth complete safely?
What should youth not be exposed to?
Who can mentor them?
