Chapter 12: Learn From Black Landholding History
Core Question
What can history teach us about land, self-government, and stewardship?
Understand
History is evidence.
The blueprint is the product.
Black communities have long understood that land is more than possession.
Land can become address, safety, dignity, food, school, church, business district, meeting space, and political base.
Mound Bayou showed the power of land and self-determination.
Independence Heights showed the importance of governance and place.
Greenwood showed that business districts need ecosystems.
Hayti showed that ownership, services, and circulation can create community power.
Harlem showed that cultural value needs ownership of stages, platforms, rooms, and rights.
History also shows vulnerability.
Land and property can be attacked through violence, law, policy, roads, lending, taxation, zoning, development, and neglect.
The society should use history to strengthen stewardship.
Not nostalgia.
Strategy.
Discuss
What historical lesson speaks to our property situation?
Where did land create power?
Where was property attacked or extracted?
What does history warn us to protect?
What modern version of stewardship do we need?
Build: Property History Reflection
History lesson selected:

What did this community build or protect?

What threatened it?

What lesson applies to us?

What action should this lesson produce?

How will we teach this to youth or members?

Chapter Outputs
[ ] Historical example selected
 [ ] Stewardship lesson named
 [ ] Threat identified
 [ ] Modern action chosen
